      "turn": 1,
      "actor": "user",
      "content": "You are the gsd-codebase-mapper agent assigned to CONCERNS.md generation.\n\n## TASK: Deep Scan CONCERNS.md ONLY\n\nWrite `.planning/codebase/CONCERNS.md` with MINIMUM 300 lines and MAXIMUM actionable depth.\n\n## REQUIREMENTS:\n\n1. **Overview** (5-10 lines) - What this document covers and why it matters\n\n2. **Critical Issues (P0)** - Issues needing immediate attention\n   - For each: title, description, affected files (backtick paths with line numbers), impact, recommended fix\n\n3. **Technical Debt (P1)** - Accumulated shortcuts and legacy code\n   - For each: what the debt is, where it lives (file:line), how it accumulated, estimated effort to fix\n\n4. **Security Concerns (P1)** - Security-related issues\n   - For each: vulnerability type, affected code (file:line), risk level, mitigation\n\n5. **Performance Issues (P2)** - Performance bottlenecks\n   - For each: where the bottleneck is (file:line), impact on users/systems, optimization opportunity\n\n6. **Code Quality Issues (P2)** - Code smell, duplication, complexity\n   - For each: pattern name, location (file:line), how widespread, recommended refactoring\n\n7. **Architectural Fragility (P2)** - Areas that are brittle or hard to change\n   - For each: why it's fragile, what could break, how to improve\n\n8. **Test Coverage Gaps (P2)** - Areas lacking adequate tests\n   - For each: untested module, risk level, what tests are needed\n\n9. **Dependency Concerns (P2)** - Outdated or risky dependencies\n   - For each: package name, current version, risk, recommended action\n\n10. **Priority Summary** - Table ranking all issues by severity and effort\n\n## CRITICAL RULES:\n- Every concern MUST reference actual code with backtick file paths and line numbers\n- Use grep, glob, and read tools to find real issues - DO NOT invent or assume\n- Search for: TODOs, FIXMEs, HACKs, deprecated patterns, circular dependencies, missing types, error handling gaps\n- Check package.json for outdated dependencies\n- Verify test coverage by examining test files\n- Look for security patterns: eval(), dynamic imports without validation, hardcoded secrets, missing input validation\n\n## VALIDATION:\nAfter writing, verify line count with: wc -l .planning/codebase/CONCERNS.md\nMust be MINIMUM 300 lines.\n\nReturn: file path and ACTUAL line count.",
